or two nouns in German, French and English. Having distinguished compounds from phrases on structural and semantic-functional grounds, the author claims that compounds are by their nature more appropriate to be stored in the mental lexicon than phrases and supports his argument with empirical evidence from new psycholinguistic studies. In sum, the book maintains the separation between compounds and phrases and reflects upon its cognitive consequences.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEnglish languagexComparative, grammar. 0aEnglish languagexGrammar, Comparative. 0aFrench languagexComparative, grammar. 0aFrench languagexGrammar, Comparative. 0aGerman languagexComparative, grammar. 0aGerman languagexGrammar, Comparative. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxAnalysis. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxMorphology. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 0aMemoryxPsycholinguistics. 0aMemoryxPsychological aspects. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSemantic memory. 4aAdjektivphrase. 4aKompositum. 4aMentales Lexikon. 4aNominalphrase. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAdjective Phrase.  aCompound.  aMental Lexicon.  aNoun Phrase.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2018 Part 1z978311076248808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z978311071955008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018 Englishz978311060407808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018z9783110603170oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz